  "prompt": "How are bounding boxes in images formed in computer vision?",
  "response": "In computer vision, bounding boxes are formed through several common methods:\n\n1. Manual Annotation\n- Human annotators draw rectangular boxes around objects\n- Precisely mark object locations in training images\n- Time-consuming but provides ground truth data\n\n2. Object Detection Algorithms\na) Traditional Methods:\n- Sliding window technique\n- Selective search algorithms\n- HOG (Histogram of Oriented Gradients) + SVM\n\nb) Deep Learning Approaches:\n- YOLO (You Only Look Once)\n- R-CNN family (Faster R-CNN, Mask R-CNN)\n- SSD (Single Shot Detector)\n- RetinaNet\n\n3. Key Steps in Automatic Bounding Box Generation\n- Image preprocessing\n- Feature extraction\n- Region proposal generation\n- Classification and regression\n- Non-max suppression to remove redundant boxes\n\n4. Characteristics Defined\n- Top-left coordinates (x, y)\n- Width\n- Height\n- Confidence score\n- Class label\n\n5. Advanced Techniques\n- Anchor boxes\n- Multi-scale detection\n- IoU (Intersection over Union) for precision\n- Advanced architectures like YOLO v5, v7\n\nEach method balances speed, accuracy, and computational complexity.",
